{"title_page": "Adaptations of The Wizard of Oz", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Adaptations of ''The Wizard of Oz''}}\n[[File:Tin-Man-poster-Hamlin.jpeg|thumb|Poster for Fred R. Hamlin's 1902 musical extravaganza, the first major theatrical adaptation of ''The Wizard of Oz'']]\n\n''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1900 [[children's literature|children's novel]] written by American author [[L. Frank Baum]]. Since its first publication in 1900, it has been adapted many times: for film, television, theatre, books, comics, games, and other media.\n\n==Film==\n'''Live-Action'''\n* ''[[The Fairylogue and Radio-Plays]]'' is a 1908 multimedia presentation made by [[L. Frank Baum]] which featured the young silent film actress [[Romola Remus]].\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1910 film)|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 15-minute 1910 film, based on the [[The Wizard of Oz (1902 stage play)|1902 stage musical]], directed by [[Otis Turner]], and may have featured [[Bebe Daniels]] as Dorothy.\n* ''[[The Patchwork Girl of Oz (1914 film)|The Patchwork Girl of Oz]]'' is a 1914 adaptation produced by Baum's live-action motion picture company, [[The Oz Film Manufacturing Company]]. It follows the adventures of Ojo, Unc Nunkle, and Patchwork Girl in their quest for the ingredients needed for a magic potion.\n* ''[[His Majesty, the Scarecrow of Oz]]'' is a loose 1914 adaptation by Baum that became the basis for the book ''[[The Scarecrow of Oz]]''.\n* ''[[The Magic Cloak of Oz]]'' (1914) is another in the series produced by Baum himself via The Oz Film Manufacturing Company. It follows the story of Fluff, the unhappiest person in Oz, and a magic cloak fairies devised for him to grant her one wish.\n* ''[[Wizard of Oz (1925 film)|Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1925 film, directed by [[Larry Semon]] in collaboration with [[Frank Joslyn Baum]] and featuring a young [[Oliver Hardy]].\n\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is the 1939 musical film by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], directed by [[Victor Fleming]] and starring [[Judy Garland]], [[Ray Bolger]], [[Jack Haley]], [[Bert Lahr]], [[Margaret Hamilton (actress)|Margaret Hamilton]], and [[Frank Morgan]]. It is the story's best-known adaptation.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Land of Oz]]'' is a 1969 low-budget children's film adaptation of ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz]]'', directed by [[Barry Mahon]].\n* ''[[Ay\u015fecik ve Sihirli C\u00fcceler R\u00fcyalar \u00dclkesinde]]'' is a 1971 Turkish film, directed by [[Tun\u00e7 Ba\u015faran]] known to bootleggers as \"The Turkish Wizard of Oz\".\n* ''[[Oz (1976 film)|Oz]]'' is a 1976 Australian rock musical film, also known as ''Oz \u2013 A Rock 'n' Roll Road Movie'' or ''20th Century Oz''.\n* ''[[The Wiz (film)|The Wiz]]'' is a 1978 film directed by [[Sidney Lumet]] starring [[Diana Ross]] as Dorothy and [[Michael Jackson]] as the Scarecrow, based on the [[The Wiz|Broadway musical of the same name]].\n* ''[[Return to Oz]]'' is a 1985 film by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], directed by [[Walter Murch]] and starring [[Fairuza Balk]] as Dorothy.\n* ''[[The Wizard of the City of Emeralds]]'' is a 1994 Russian film version of [[Alexander Melentyevich Volkov]]'s \"adaptation\" of Baum's original book.\n* ''[[The Muppets' Wizard of Oz]]'' (2005) Starring [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Queen Latifah]] and [[The Muppets]]. [[Miss Piggy]] plays all of the witches, [[Pepe the Prawn|Pepe]] plays Toto, [[Kermit the Frog|Kermit]] plays the Scarecrow, [[Gonzo the Great|Gonzo]] plays the Tin Man, and [[Fozzie the Bear|Fozzie]] plays the Lion.\n* ''[[Apocalypse Oz]]'' (2006) is a [[short film]] parody of ''The Wizard of Oz'' and ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''.\n* ''[[After the Wizard]]'' is a 2012 independent film as a modern-day semi-sequel to the story.\n* ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]'' is a 2013 film by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], directed by [[Sam Raimi]] and starring [[James Franco]] and [[Mila Kunis]].\n* ''[[OzLand]]'' (2014) is an independent fantasy/sci-fi drama film inspired by characters and events from the book, which plays a crucial role.\n\n'''Animation'''\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1933 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1933 animated short directed by Ted Eshbaugh.\n* ''[[Journey Back to Oz]]'' is a 1971 animated film, begun in 1962, finished in 1971 and eventually released between 1972\u201374.\n* ''[[Once Upon a Time (1976 film)|Once Upon a Time]]'' is a 1976 film in which Maria and Mary-Lou get sucked down a well into Holleland. It is loosely based upon, and also pays homage to, ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* ''[[Legends of Oz: Dorothy's Return]]'' (2014) is an American-Indian 3D animated musical adaptation of ''[[Dorothy of Oz (book)|Dorothy of Oz]]'' by [[Roger S. Baum]] and stars [[Lea Michele]].\n* ''[[Guardians of Oz]]'' is a 2015 [[Mexico|Mexican]]-[[India]]n 3D computer animated adventure film directed by Alberto Mar. It features an original story and new characters.\n* ''[[The Steam Engines of Oz]]'' is a 2018 [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Animated film]] directed by [[Sean O'Reilly]] which is produced by [[Arcana Studio]]. It tells the story of Oz a hundred years later and features new characters as well as old ones.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://collider.com/william-shatner-on-the-steam-engines-of-oz-and-his-life-long-love-of-animation/|title=William Shatner on 'The Steam Engines of Oz' and His Life-Long Love of Animation|date=2018-06-05|work=Collider|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nMany of the television programs cited in this list are not strict adaptions of ''The Wizard of Oz''; rather, they have reinterpreted aspects of the book, such as characters and plot, to create sequels, prequels or side-plots, which are inspired by Baum's original text.\n* ''[[The Suite Life on Deck]]'' episode \"Twister\"\n* ''[[Back at the Barnyard]]'' the last part of the episode \"Lights! Camera! Moo!\"\n* ''[[Kappa Mikey]]'' \"The Wizard of Ozu\"\n* ''[[Rainbow Road to Oz]]'' was a proposed [[Walt Disney]] live-action production. A preview segment aired in 1957 on the ''[[Disneyland (TV series)|Disneyland]]'' TV show, featuring [[Darlene Gillespie]] as Dorothy, [[Annette Funicello]] as Ozma, [[Bobby Burgess]] as the Scarecrow, [[Doreen Tracey]] as Scraps, the Patchwork Girl, and [[Jimmie Dodd]] as the Cowardly Lion.\n* ''The Land of Oz'' is the 1960 premiere episode of ''The Shirley Temple Show'', known in previous seasons as ''[[Shirley Temple's Storybook]]'', and no relation to the ''Shirley Temple Theatre'' which showcased old Temple films. This adaptation of ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz]]'' was written by [[Frank Gabrielson]] and directed by William Corrigan. [[William Asher]] produced. The cast included [[Shirley Temple]] (Ozma/Tip), [[Ben Blue]] (The Scarecrow), [[Agnes Moorehead]] (Mombi), [[Sterling Holloway]] (Jack Pumpkinhead), [[Gil Lamb]] (The Tin Woodman), [[Jonathan Winters]] (Lord Nikidik), [[Arthur Treacher]] (Graves the Butler), and [[Mel Blanc]] (Voice of the sawhorse).\n* ''[[Tales of the Wizard of Oz]]'' is a [[1961 in television|1961]] animated series of short episodes based on the Oz characters from the book.\n* ''[[Off to See the Wizard]]'' is a 1967 television anthology series which showcased then-recent MGM family films. The Oz characters appeared in animated segments.\n* ''[[Return to Oz (TV program)|Return to Oz]]'' is a [[1964 in television|1964]] animated television special sequel-cum-remake of the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]], based on the artistic renderings of the characters in the [[Tales of the Wizard of Oz|1961 animated series]].\n* ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', on February 16, 1980, had a sketch called ''The Incredible Man'', a parody of both ''The Wizard of Oz'' and the annual TV broadcast of the film that was standard at the time.   \n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1982 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a feature-length anime adaptation of the story produced by [[Toho]] in 1982 and directed by Fumihiko Takayama, with music by [[Joe Hisaishi]]. The English version of the movie stars [[Aileen Quinn]] as the voice of Dorothy and [[Lorne Greene]] as the Wizard. Original songs are sung by Aileen Quinn in the English version, with lyrics by [[Sammy Cahn]] and Allen Byrnes. It was released in the United States before it premiered in Japan. In the U.S., it was released on video and syndicated to local television stations.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1986 TV series)|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', an episodic anime adaptation of four of Baum's Oz books, was created in 1986. It consists of 52 episodes and follows the story of Dorothy and her adventures in Oz with the Tin Woodman, Cowardly Lion, and Scarecrow. It continues on to the story of [[Princess Ozma|Ozma]] and [[Mombi]], and follows the events in other Oz books. In 1987, HBO purchased the rights to the series and edited together key episodes of the series into a series of movies, which aired as a television mini-series. [[Margot Kidder]] was the narrator. Production for the English version was done by the Canadian studio [[Cinar]].\n* In the 1987 series ''[[Hello Kitty's Furry Tale Theater]]'', ''The Wizard of Paws'' is the first part of first episode. The story begins when after a huge tornado, Hello Dorothy (Hello Kitty) gets whisked away from her home of Catfish to The Land of Paws. Upon arrival, she is welcomed by the Tin Penguin (Tuxedo J Orville Sam), The Scarecrow (Chip), the Cowardly Rabbit (My Melody) and the Munchkits. They thank Hello Dorothy, as the Wicked Witch (Catnip) was about to turn them into cat litter. Just as that is said, the Wicked Witch arises from the house as hello kitty picks up the ruby collar. After crushing the Wicked Witch and taking her collar, the witch plans revenge on Hello Dorothy to take back her precious collar. Dorothy then begins her journey back to the land of Catfish with the penguin, scarecrow and rabbit in order to return home along the yellow block road.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (TV series)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', an animated series based on the 1939 film, was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] during the [[1990 in television|1990\u20131991 TV season]]. The cartoon featured Dorothy returning to Oz, reuniting with her four friends, and journeying through the magical realm in an attempt to rescue the Wizard from a resurrected Witch of the West.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Galaxy of Oz]]'' (''Space Oz no B\u00f4ken'') is a [[1990 in television|1990]] Japanese anime series involving Dorothy and her friends in a futuristic setting, traveling the \"Galaxy of Oz\". It was truncated to 76 minutes and dubbed for the American release.\n* ''[[The Oz Kids]]'' is a [[1996 in television|1996]] animated series by [[Hyperion Pictures]] and [[Nelvana]] featuring the children of the original characters.\n* ''[[Tim Burton's unrealized projects#2000s|Tim Burton's Lost In Oz]]'' is a [[2000 in television|2000]] unrealized television pilot script written by [[Trey Callaway]] with [[Tim Burton]] as executive producer. Key scenes were filmed by [[Michael Katleman]].\n* ''Lost in Oz'' is a [[2002 in television|2002]] television pilot, never broadcast. It is a sequel to the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]].\n* The ''[[Futurama]]'' episode \"[[Anthology of Interest II]]\" is a retelling of the Oz story, shown as a dream of one of the show's characters.\n* The 100th episode of the television comedy-drama show ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', titled \"[[My Way Home (Scrubs)|My Way Home]]\" is a homage to the ''Wizard of Oz''.\n* ''[[Tin Man (TV miniseries)|Tin Man]]'' is a three-part miniseries released in December 2007 on the [[Syfy|Sci-fi Channel]] by [[RHI Entertainment]] and Syfy. The miniseries, directed by [[Nick Willing]] and starring [[Zooey Deschanel]], [[Richard Dreyfuss]], [[Alan Cumming]], [[Raoul Trujillo]], [[Neal McDonough]], and [[Kathleen Robertson]], is a re-imagined version of ''The Wizard of Oz'' with a heavy science fantasy emphasis. The heroine, D.G., is a descendant of Dorothy Gale. Other humans, called \"Slippers\" by the people of Oz, have visited Oz since Gale's fateful adventure. The series portrays a future version of Oz, thereby making the mini-series both a sequel and a re-imagining.\n* ''OzEnders'', a 2003 charity special of ''[[EastEnders]]'', saw the characters in a spoof remake of ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''. [[June Brown]] starred as [[Dot Cotton|Dorothy Cotton]], [[Jon Culshaw]] as [[Ozzy Osbourne]], and [[Adam Woodyatt]] as [[Ian Beale]].\n* ''[[Dorothy and the Witches of Oz]]'' is a 2011 television mini-series directed by Leigh Scott, based on the novels ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'', ''Ozma of Oz'', ''The Road to Oz'', and ''The Magic of Oz'' by Baum.\n* An episode of ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'' shows SpongeBob and Patrick going to see Mr. Magic. As in ''The Wizard of Oz'', Mr. Magic, who was thought to be a giant, magical head, is revealed to be a powerless, little man.\n* In 2012 the [[Nickelodeon]] show ''[[The Fresh Beat Band]]'' did a remake in a one hour episode called \u201cThe Wizard of Song\u201d with Mariana as Dorothy, Kiki as Tin-women, Twist as Scarecrow, and Shout as the Lion.\n* ''[[Tom and Jerry and the Wizard of Oz]]'' is a ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' direct-to-video film, the first to be made for [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]]. It first appeared on [[Cartoon Network]] on August 13, 2011. It was followed by a sequel, ''[[Tom and Jerry: Back to Oz]]'', released February 3, 2016.\n* In an episode of ''[[Rugrats]]'', ''[[No Place Like Home (Rugrats episode)|No Place Like Home]]'', Susie dreams of a land like Oz after having her tonsils removed.\n* In an episode of ''[[The Wonder Pets]]'' ''In the Land of Oz'', The Wonder Pets get caught in a tornado and blown to the magical Land of Oz, and they need help getting home by The Scarecrow, The Tin Man and The Cowardly Lion by going to the Emerald City.\n* An episode of ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' is titled ''[[Wizard of Odd]]''. In order to wash their house quickly, Phineas and Ferb build a contraption that spins it around, causing Candace to become so dizzy, she collapses. She soon finds herself in the magical land of Odd where Isabella, Dr. Doofenshmirtz, Jeremy, Buford, and Baljeet are remarkably like the characters from ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* An episode of ''[[Mickey Mouse Clubhouse]]'', \"Minnie's The Wizard of Dizz\", places Minnie and Pluto in the roles of Dorothy and Toto. Goofy, Mickey, and Donald appear as the Scarecrow, Tin Mouse, and Lion. Clarabelle Cow appears as the good witch, Pete as the bad witch, and Ludwig von Drake as the wizard.\n* The characters Dorothy Gale and The Wicked Witch of the West make appearances in the 2014 episode \"Slumber Party\" from the ninth season of the television series ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''. Dorothy is revealed to be a hunter of evil and the daughter of [[L. Frank Baum]]. The Tin Man, Cowardly Lion, and Scarecrow all make appearances. The [[Supernatural (season 10)|season 10]] episode \"There's No Place Like Home\" tells of a war for the Emerald City in which the Wizard has been split into good and dark sides.\n* The Wicked Witch of the West is the main antagonist in the second half of the third season of the ABC/Disney television series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''. In this version, the wicked witch was abandoned by her mother in the woods where a tornado took her to Oz.\n* ''[[Emerald City (TV series)|Emerald City]]'' is a television series in development by [[Universal Television]] that drew inspiration from L. Frank Baum's original 14 books. Created by [[Matthew Arnold (director)|Matthew Arnold]], in January 2014 it had been officially picked up by [[NBC]] for 10 episodes.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/23/nbc-wizard-of-oz-emerald-city_n_3805939.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Leigh | last=Weingus | title='The Wizard Of Oz' Just Keeps Getting Hotter | date=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/20/nbc-picks-up-emerald-city_n_4630556.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Jason | last=Hughes | title=Welcome To 'Emerald City'}}</ref> In August 2014, it was reported that NBC would not be proceeding with the series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=NBC Drops Limited Series ''Emerald City''|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nbc-drops-limited-series-emerald-727155|website=The Live Feed: [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=23 August 2014|date=22 August 2014}}</ref> In April 2015, NBC reversed course and announced that the series would move forward under the leadership of executive producer and writer [[David Schulner]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/emerald-city-resurrected-nbc-series-1201410547 | work=Deadline.com | first=Nellie | last=Andreeva | title=\u2018Emerald City\u2019 Resurrected By NBC With Straight-To-Series Order, New Writer | date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* On December 3, 2015, [[NBC]] aired the live television production ''[[The Wiz Live!]]'' Produced by Craig Zadan and Neil Meron, it is a performance of a new adaptation of the 1975 Broadway musical ''[[The Wiz]]'', a soul/R&B reinterpretation of L. Frank Baum's ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz''. The performance aired live from [[Grumman Studios]] in Bethpage, New York.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web |title=The Wiz Live! Defied The Skeptics, Returns For A Second Round |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/12/19/460313984/the-wiz-live-defied-the-skeptics-returns-for-a-second-round |date=December 20, 2015 |publisher=NPR |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=NBC>{{cite web |title=The Wiz Live! |url=http://www.nbc.com/the-wiz-live |publisher=NBC |accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n* On June 26, 2015, [[Amazon Video]] released an original 24-minute pilot for an animated series, ''[[Lost In Oz (TV series)|Lost in Oz]]''.  On November 2, 2016, it was re-released with additional content under the title ''[[Lost in Oz: Extended Adventure]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lost in Oz (TV Series 2015\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4677846|accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref> The series aired on August 4, 2017.\n* ''[[Dorothy and the Wizard of Oz]]'' (originally ''Dorothy: Princess of Oz'' and ''Dorothy of Oz'') is an animated series produced by [[Warner Bros. Animation]]. It was released in June 2017 for [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]]'s SVOD service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/boomerang-cartoon-streaming-subscription-time-warner-turner-wb-1202003660/|title=Turner, Warner Bros. to Launch Boomerang Cartoon Streaming-Subscription Service for $5 Monthly|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2017-03-07|work=Variety|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en-US}}</ref> Clips of the series were revealed in the Boomerang upfront for 2017.<ref>https://vimeo.com/200963930</ref>\n* In the ''[[Victorious]]'' episode \"April Fools' Blank\", the main characters retell the story in the girls' toilet of the Hollywood Arts.\n* In the rebooted TV series [[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|Dynasty]] episode \"That Witch\", one of the main characters [[Fallon Carrington Colby|Fallon]], gets knocked by an ornament and sees visions of herself as Dorothy in the Wizard of Oz.\n\n==Theatre==\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1902 stage play)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', the first [[musical theater|musical]] version of ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'', was produced by L. Frank Baum and W. W. Denslow (with music by composer [[Paul Tietjens]]) in [[Chicago]] in 1902 and moved to New York in 1903. It used many of the same characters, and was aimed more at adult audiences. It had a long, successful run on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. Baum added numerous political references to the script, mentioning President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], Senator [[Mark Hanna]], and [[John D. Rockefeller]] by name.<ref>Swartz, ''Before the Rainbow'', pp 34, 47, 56</ref> Many existing songs that had nothing to do with the story were interpolated. Baum followed with two additional Oz musicals, ''[[The Woggle-Bug]]'' (1905) and ''[[The Tik-Tok Man of Oz]]'' (1913). Both were panned as rehashes rather than sequels; ''Tik-Tok'' did better than ''The Woggle-Bug'' but neither made it to Broadway.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1942 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1942 musical using songs from the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]]. It was adapted by [[Frank Gabrielson]] for the [[St. Louis Municipal Opera]]. The piece continues to receive frequent revivals.<ref name=\"stage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondtherainbow2oz.com/stagethewizard.html|title=We're Off To Stage The Wizard of Oz|accessdate=2007-07-15|last=Raymond|first=Kurt|work=Beyond the Rainbow to Oz website| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714185622/http://www.beyondtherainbow2oz.com/stagethewizard.html| archivedate= 14 July 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tams-witmark.com/musicals/wizardrsc.html |title=Wizard of Oz (R.S.C. 1988) |accessdate=2007-07-15 |year=2005 |publisher=Tams\u2013Witmark Music Library |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701001053/http://www.tams-witmark.com/musicals/wizardrsc.html |archivedate=1 July 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 1959, the popular ice skating show ''[[Holiday on Ice]]'' included a condensed version of ''The Wizard of Oz''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vintage Holiday On Ice Show Programs|url=http://www.icesk8.com/collect/progrm01.htm|work=Ice Skating Accessories Galore Collectible Skating Programs|publisher=Lisa Ilona Hlavacek|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wiz]]'' is a 1975 musical with music and lyrics by [[Charlie Smalls]], exclusively featuring [[African American]] actors. [[Stephanie Mills]] starred as Dorothy in the original Broadway cast. The production won the 1975 [[Tony Award]] for [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]]. [[Geoffrey Holder]] directed a 1984 Broadway revival, which also featured Mills as Dorothy.\n* ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz (musical)|The Marvelous Land of Oz]]'' is a 1981 musical by Thomas W. Olson, Gary Briggle and [[Richard Dworsky]]. The original production, which included Briggle as the Scarecrow, was taped and shown on television.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1987 adaptation by [[John Kane (writer)|John Kane]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] based on the novel and 1939 film, which hews more closely to the film's screenplay than the 1942 version. This show ran through 1989 and continues to be frequently revived and toured.<ref>[http://www.columbiaartiststheatricals.com/Shows/wizard_oz.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612104931/http://www.columbiaartiststheatricals.com/Shows/wizard_oz.html|date=June 12, 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/Follow+yellow+brick+road/3862399/story.html]{{dead link|date=November 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wizard of A.I.D.S.]]'' is a 1987 adaptation of the Oz story which serves as an [[AIDS]] education tool.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz Live]]'' (1989\u20131990) is an arena touring production in celebration of the film's 50th anniversary. The production featured a pre-recorded soundtrack.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz in Concert: Dreams Come True]]'' was a 1995 concert performance of the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s adaptation at [[Lincoln Center]], featuring celebrity actors such as [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]] as Dorothy, [[Jackson Browne]] as the Scarecrow, [[Roger Daltrey]] as the Tin Man, [[Nathan Lane]] as the Lion, and [[Joel Grey]] as the Wizard (a role he later reprised in [[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]). The production also featured [[Debra Winger]], [[Natalie Cole]], and [[Lucie Arnaz]].\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz on Tour]]'' was a 1998 touring production of the 1987 RSC version that originally played in the [[Madison Square Garden]] theatre in May 1997. [[Roseanne Barr]] was the Wicked Witch, replaced by [[Eartha Kitt]] in 1998 and [[JoAnne Worley]] and [[Liliane Montevecchi]] in 1999. [[Mickey Rooney]] was the Wizard. The production played at Madison Square Garden from May 1997 to May 1999. The touring production ran from May 1998 to late 1999.\n* ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]'' (2003\u2013Present) is a 2003 Broadway and West End musical based on the book ''[[Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West]]'' by [[Gregory Maguire]]. [[Universal Pictures]] had bought [[film rights]] to the 1995 novel when composer and lyricist [[Stephen Schwartz (composer)|Stephen Schwartz]] convinced the company to adapt the novel into a musical instead. Schwartz wrote ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''{{'}}s music and lyrics and it premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in October 2003.<ref name=\"Christie\"/>\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (musical)]]'' is a 2000 musical that premiered in Toronto. The show was revived in 2002, 2010 and again in 2017.\n* In 2005 there was a children musical in [[Balver H\u00f6hle]]\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (2011 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 2011 West End musical, building on the 1939 film songs and script with new material by Tim Rice and Andrew Lloyd Webber. It began previews on February 7, 2011 and officially opened on March 1. [[Danielle Hope]], of the [[BBC]] television Series ''[[Over the Rainbow (2010 TV series)|Over the Rainbow]]'', appeared as Dorothy. [[Michael Crawford]] plays the role of the Wizard.\n* ''The [[Royal New Zealand Ballet]] premiered a ''Wizard of Oz'' ballet in May 2016 at the [[St. James Theatre, Wellington]] using a score created by composer [[Francis Poulenc]]. The ballet then toured New Zealand throughout May and June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=RNZB website|url=http://rnzb.org.nz/shows/the-wizard-of-oz/|work=RNZB show page|publisher=Royal New Zealand Ballet|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n* In 2015, a [[Costa Rica]]n adaptation of both the novel and the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]] titled ''El OH!8'' was premiered. The stage play is an open criticism of the country's laws against [[LGBT marriage]], using the original plot and similar musical numbers.\n* In 2018, musical \"\u010carobnjak iz Oza\" premieref in Children's Theatre in [[Osijek]], Croatia.<ref name=\"\u010carobnjak iz Oza\">{{cite web | title=Premijera mjuzikla \u010carobnjak iz Oza | trans-title=The Musical Premiere of the Wizard of Oz | website=Osnovna \u0161kola August \u0160enoa Osijek | url=http://os-asenoa-os.skole.hr/?news_hk=1&news_id=1962&mshow=1534#mod_news | language=hr | access-date=2018-05-16 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517005934/http://os-asenoa-os.skole.hr/?news_hk=1&news_id=1962&mshow=1534#mod_news | archive-date=2018-05-17 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nThere are over [[List of Oz books|40 canonical Oz books]], including 14 by Baum, all of which are considered \"official\" sequels or prequels to ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]''. In addition, the following books use the Oz milieu as settings for their tales:\n* ''[[The Wizard of the Emerald City]]'', a 1939 children's novel by Russian writer [[Alexander Melentyevich Volkov]], is a loose translation of ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz''. It was adapted into animated series (1973)<ref>{{cite web|title=Volshebnik izumrudnogo goroda (1974)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0069653/|work=IMDb.com|publisher=IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> and a live action film (1994).<ref>{{cite web|title=Volshebnik izumrudnogo goroda (1994)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0111641/|work=IMDb.com|publisher=IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> It has five sequels by the same author.\n* ''[[The Number of the Beast (novel)|The Number of the Beast]]'' is a science fiction novel written by [[Robert A. Heinlein]] in 1980. The story uses Oz as one of many alternate universe settings in which events take place, alongside alternate versions of the setting's Earth.\n* ''[[A Barnstormer in Oz]]'' is a 1982 novel by [[Philip Jos\u00e9 Farmer]] in which a pilot named Hank Stover, who is Dorothy's son, is transported to Oz when his plane becomes lost in a green cloud over Kansas.\n* ''[[Was (novel)|Was]]'', [[Geoff Ryman]]'s 1992 [[parallel novel]], imagines three interwoven narratives: one of a real-life \"Dorothy Gael\" whose experiences are far from wonderful, the second loosely based on Judy Garland's own childhood, and the third story featuring a gay male actor who loves the 1939 film. ''Was'' was republished in 2014 by [[Small Beer Press]].\n* ''Home from Oz'' (Thomas Nelson, 1994) and ''The Oz Syndrome'' (Hillcrest Publishers, 2001) are two books penned by psychologist and professor, Dr.[[Michael A. O'Donnell]] which deal with the Oz characters and the [[MGM]] musical version from a psychological point of view.\n* ''[[Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West]]'', a revisionist look at the land and characters of Oz, was published in 1995 by [[Gregory Maguire]]. Instead of depicting Dorothy, the novel focuses on [[Elphaba]], the future Wicked Witch of the West. ''[[The Independent]]'' characterized the novel as \"an adult read reflecting on the nature of being an outcast, society's pressures to conform, and the effects of oppression and fascism\".<ref name=\"Christie\">{{cite news|title=Wicked: tales of the witches of Oz |author=Christie, Nicola |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/wicked--tales-of-the-witches-of-oz-412263.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=August 17, 2006 |accessdate=February 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705183310/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/wicked--tales-of-the-witches-of-oz-412263.html |archivedate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Wicked'' has three sequels: ''[[Son of a Witch]]'' (2005), ''[[A Lion Among Men]]'' (2008) and ''[[Out of Oz]]'' (2011). ''Wicked'' was adapted into a 2003 stage musical.\n* ''[[Oz Reimagined: New Tales from the Emerald City and Beyond]]'' is a 2013 anthology edited by Douglas Cohen & [[John Joseph Adams]] published by [[Amazon Publishing]]'s 47North imprint.<ref>{{cite web|title=You\u2019ve never seen the Wizard of Oz like this before)|url=http://io9.com/5953680/youve-never-seen-the-wizard-of-oz-like-this-before|work=io9|publisher=io9|accessdate=22 October 2012|author=Jane Anders, Charlie |date=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Dorothy Must Die]]'' is a 2014 young adult book by Danielle Paige and makes up part of the ''Dorothy Must Die'' series, which also includes three prequel novellas: ''No Place Like Oz'', ''The Witch Must Burn'' and ''The Wizard Returns'', which were published together in March 2015. The next three prequel novellas, ''Heart of Tin'', ''The Straw King'' and ''Ruler of Beasts'', were released in a paperback book titled ''Dorothy Must Die Stories: Volume #2'' in June 28, 2016. Two more novellas, ''Order of the Wicked'' and ''Dark Side of the Rainbow'', have also been released. A sequel titled ''[[The Wicked Will Rise]]'' was published on March 30, 2015, following the events of ''Dorothy Must Die''. The third installment of the series titled ''Yellow Brick War'' was published on March 15, 2016. The fourth and final book, ''The End of Oz'', was published on March 14, 2017.\n\n==Comics==\n[[File:WiZardOz.jpg|thumb|260px|''The Wizard of Oz'' ([[Dell Comics]], June 1956). Cover art by Mel Crawford.]]\n* MGM's ''Marvelous Wizard of Oz'' was the first joint publishing venture between [[DC Comics]] and [[Marvel Comics]].<ref>{{cite book|last=McAvennie|first= Michael|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1970s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 165 |quote = The Yellow Brick Road from Munchkin Land to the Emerald City was also wide enough to accommodate DC and Marvel as they produced their first-ever joint publication&nbsp;... Roy Thomas scripted a faithful, seventy-two page adaptation of Dorothy Gale's adventure, while John Buscema's artwork depicted the landscape of Oz in lavish detail.}}</ref>\n* Marvel Treasury of Oz printed ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz]]''.\n* One of the issues of ''[[Classics Illustrated Junior]]'' was a condensed version of ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* The comic book series ''[[Oz Squad]]'' features an adult Dorothy and her original companions from ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' as a [[covert operations]] group protecting Oz from threats both within its borders and from the \"real world\".\n* ''The Oz-Wonderland War'' is a comics story in which the people of Oz fight together with the characters of [[Lewis Carroll]]'s ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]'' against the villainous [[Nome King]]. It also starred [[Captain Carrot]] and the [[Zoo Crew]] and was originally intended to be the comic's issues #21\u201326. The comic, however, was cancelled at #20, and the story was subsequently presented as a mini-series.\n* ''[[Dorothy of Oz (manhwa)|Dorothy of Oz]]'' (Korean:''Dorosi'') is a [[manhwa]] (Korean comic) by Son Hee-joon about an ordinary girl named Mara Shin who winds up in a science-fantasy realm called \"Oz\". She meets up with this realm's version of the Scarecrow, the Tin Woodsman and the Cowardly Lion, and follows the Yellow Brick Road to find her way home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animeondvd.com/reviews2/manga/manga.php?manga_view=4079 |title=AnimeOnDVD.com review of Dorothy of Oz |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506094208/http://www.animeondvd.com/reviews2/manga/manga.php?manga_view=4079 |archivedate=6 May 2008 }}</ref>\n* The comic book ''[[Dorothy (comic book)|Dorothy]]'' was launched by Illusive Arts Entertainment in November 2005. Presented in semi-[[Photo strip|fumetti]] style using digitally altered photographs, this retelling of Baum's story has been updated to 2005 and features model Catie Fisher as 16-year-old Dorothy Gale, a disaffected youth with dyed hair and piercings who steals her uncle's car and runs away from home; until she encounters a tornado and is knocked unconscious.\n* An erotic re-telling of the story is featured in ''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]'', a graphic novel by [[Alan Moore]] and [[Melinda Gebbie]] first published in its entirety in 2006. In this book, an adult Dorothy meets [[Alice (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Alice]] from ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' and [[Wendy Darling]] from ''[[Peter Pan]]'' and the trio recount the stories of their respective works as allegories for their sexual awakenings.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (comics)|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', published by [[Marvel Comics]].\n* ''[[Marvel Fairy Tales]]'' features a retelling of ''The Wizard of Oz'' starring Marvel characters, such as the [[She-Hulk]] as Dorothy and the [[Scarlet Witch]] as the Wicked Witch of the West.   \n* The Steam Engines of Oz is a graphic novel series published by [[Arcana Studio]]. It is a \"steampunk re-imagining\" of [[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rotoscopers.com/2017/11/04/animated-steampunk-wizard-of-oz-set-for-2018/|title=Animated Steampunk 'Wizard of Oz' Set for 2018 {{!}} Rotoscopers|date=2017-11-04|work=Rotoscopers|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Games==\n* ''The Wonderful Game of Oz'', a board game published in 1921 by [[Parker Brothers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/14261/wonderful-game-of-oz |title=Wonderful Game of OZ |publisher=BoardGameGeek |date=May 4, 2005 |accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1985 video game)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', a 1985 illustrated [[text adventure]] game for [[Apple II]], [[Commodore 64]] and [[DOS]] systems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mocagh.org/loadpage.php?getgame=wizardoz |title=Computer Game Museum Display Case \u2013 Wizard of Oz |publisher=Mocagh.org |date=2001-07-07 |accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lysator.liu.se/adventure/Telarium_Corporation.html |title=Telarium Corporation |publisher=Lysator.liu.se |date=1930-11-09 |accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref> which combined elements of ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' and ''The Marvelous Land of Oz''. It was published by [[Windham Classics]], a subsidiary of [[Spinnaker Software]].\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (video game)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', a 1993 video game for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]], based on the 1939 film.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (arcade game)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', a coin pusher game found in video arcades.\n* ''Wizard of Land Oz'' (''\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0448\u0435\u0431\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044b \u041e\u0437''), a 1997 [[ZX Spectrum]] adventure game by Famous Faces Factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0013128 |title=Wizard of Land Oz |publisher=World of Spectrum |date= |accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref>\n* ''[[Irozuki Tincle no Koi no Balloon Trip]]'', a Japanese game which is a spin-off of ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series. It features [[Tingle (character)|Tingle]] teaming up with a tin woman, a scarecrow and a cowardly lion to cross the land. Released in 2009.\n* ''[[Emerald City Confidential]]'', a point-and-click adventure game developed by [[Dave Gilbert (game designer)|Wadjet Eye Games]] and published by casual game portal [[PlayFirst]]. Released in 2009.\n* ''RIZ-ZOAWD'', a Japanese [[role-playing video game]] for the [[Nintendo DS]], released in the US as ''[[The Wizard of Oz: Beyond the Yellow Brick Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Riz-Zoawd Hands-On Preview|url=http://www.1up.com/previews/riz-zoawd|work=1UP Games.com|publisher=1UP Games|accessdate=23 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104102742/http://www.1up.com/previews/riz-zoawd|archivedate=4 November 2012}}</ref> Released in 2008.\n* ''Wizard of Oz Slots game'' found in Casinos. The game is a five-reel video slot machine with bonus feature rounds, produced by [[Williams Electronics|WMS]] (WIlliams Gaming). Released in 2013.\n* ''The Card Game of Oz'', a 2014 game created by James C. O'Connor under his Orion's Bell label.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orion's Bell|url=http://www.orionsbell.com|publisher=Orion's Bell|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> The game is based on the original books. Series 1, ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'', was released in May 2014. Series 2, ''The Marvelous Land of Oz'', was released in August 2014 as an expansion.\n* The crossover-genre video game ''[[Lego Dimensions]]'' features a world based on the 1939 film.\n* The mobile game ''Oz: Broken Kingdom'' Is based on the world of Oz and takes place after the original story.\n\n== Music videos with Wizard of Oz themed imagery ==\n* The band [[Blues Traveler]]'s video of the song \"[[Run-Around (song)|Run-Around]]\" has a ''Wizard of Oz'' motif, with Blues Traveler playing behind a curtain in a nightclub while a young, \"hip\" and more \"photogenic\" group appears to be playing the song.\n* The band [[The Good Life (band)|The Good Life]]'s video for the song \"Heartbroke\" has characters from ''The Wizard of Oz'' going to a pastry/ice cream shop. There are two versions to this video; a \"nice\" version and a \"mean\" version. In the \"nice\" version the characters pretend to rob the shop but then purchase treats. In the \"mean\" version they violently rob the store, but the Scarecrow (who was supposed to be the getaway car) does not make it on time due to a flat tire and the would-be robbers get arrested.\n* The Black Eyed Peas music video \"Imma Be Rocking That Body\" has claimed to be the futuristic version of ''The Wizard of Oz''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kh1WyfCrnKM&list=UUrwmu-gceGOmtZeuTsn7DlQ|title=Black Eyed Peas \u2013 Imma Be (Making Of)|author=van BlackEyedPeasVEVO|date=|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* Tech N9ne's \"He's A Mental Giant\" follows the plot to the Wizard of Oz with darker imagery.<ref>{{Citation|last=TechN9neVEVO|title=Tech N9ne - He's A Mental Giant|date=2011-08-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7rhxEwJXzKo|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* \"Oooh\" by De La Soul is a music video that shows the Land of Oooh which is heavily based on the Land of Oz.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tommy Boy|title=De La Soul - Oooh (feat. Redman) [Music Video] {Clean}|date=2017-08-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uqp33KRndl8|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* Sara Evans stars as Dorothy in her music video \"Born to Fly\".<ref>{{Citation|last=saraevansVEVO|title=Sara Evans - Born To Fly|date=2009-10-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8xvhutWc67k|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* The music video for \"La la la\" by Naughty Boy featuring Sam Smith shows a young boy traveling around a city meeting characters resembling the Lion, the Tin Man, and the Scarecrow.<ref>{{Citation|last=NaughtyBoyVEVO|title=Naughty Boy - La la la ft. Sam Smith (Official Video)|date=2013-04-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3O1_3zBUKM8|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* The music video for \"Heretics and Killers\" by Protest The Hero shows the flying monkeys featured in the Wizard of Oz.<ref>{{Citation|last=Vagrant Records|title=Protest The Hero - \"Heretics and Killers\" [Official Video]|date=2006-06-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEn8HmgJxd4|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n* In 1967, [[The Seekers]] recorded \"[[Emerald City (song)|Emerald City]]\", with lyrics about a visit there, set to the melody of [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s \"[[Ode to Joy]]\".\n* [[Todd McFarlane]] created a sinister toy series called ''Twisted Land of Oz'' that portrays all of the characters as more sinister (such as the monster Toto) and adult oriented (BDSM Dorothy).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Twisted Land of OZ |url=http://www.spawn.com/features/monsters2/ |work=Spawn |publisher=Spawn.com |accessdate=23 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313070532/http://www.spawn.com/features/monsters2/ |archivedate=13 March 2012 }}</ref>\n* The rock band [[Aerosmith]] put some original audios from the 1939 movie and Steven Tyler's voice repeating some quotes of the characters in the song ''The Farm'' in the album 'Nine Lives' from 1997.\n* [[Walt Disney]] originally wanted to make an animated version of ''The Wizard Of Oz'' to serve as the follow-up to ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney's long, long journey to Oz|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2006/11/03/6565.aspx#.T-WAIFIl3IU|work=Jim Hill Media|publisher=Jim Hill Media|accessdate=23 June 2012|author=Jim Hill|date=3 November 2006}}</ref> but the film rights were bought by [[Samuel Goldwyn]], who originally intended to make it as a standard musical comedy, with [[Eddie Cantor]] as his star. However, Goldwyn ended up selling the rights to MGM.\n* [[The Felice Brothers]] wrote a song called \"Don't Wake the Scarecrow\" which features several references to ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* American McGee's ''Oz'' was a darkly, twisted series of figurines based on Baum's original ''Wizard of Oz'' characters. This series was released before McFarlane's, and was supposed to help McGee launch a franchise around this interpretation.\n* ''[[Stargate SG-1]]'' has several verbal references to ''The Wizard of Oz'', including [[Colonel Jack O'Neill]] calling [[Samantha Carter]] \"Dorothy\" when she defeated one of the show's villains.\n* The band [[Scissor Sisters]] released a song on their self-titled album called \"Return to Oz\", referencing the sequel.\n* The [[John Boorman]] film ''[[Zardoz]]'' derives its title from the ''Wizard of Oz'' (The Wi'''ZARD''' of '''OZ''').<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,942780,00.html | work=Time | title=Cinema: Celtic Twilight | date=1974-02-18 | accessdate=2010-04-23}}</ref>\n* [[Elton John]]'s album ''[[Goodbye Yellow Brick Road]]'' is a clear reference to ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* The Wiyos's album ''Twist'' is an original song cycle loosely based on ''The Wizard of Oz''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Outsight Radio Hours interviews Michael Farkas of The Wiyos on the group's Oz-inspired album Twist|url=https://archive.org/details/MichaelFarkasOnOutsightRadioHours|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Ray Bradbury]]'s short story \"[[The Exiles (Bradbury story)|The Exiles]]\" mentions the Emerald City and its inhabitants existing alongside other famous literary characters and locales on a Martian colony.\n* ''[[Big Finish Productions]]'' made a full-cast audio drama adaptation of the novel, adapted by [[Marc Platt (writer)|Marc Platt]].\n* ''[[Tom and Jerry: Back to Oz]]'' is the sequel to ''[[Tom and Jerry and the Wizard of Oz]]'' and is a ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' direct-to-video film.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\nKevin Scott Collier. ''The Wonderful Animated World of the Wizard of Oz: The Good, The Bad and The Ugly!'' CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2018. {{ISBN|172632558X}}\n\n{{Oz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wizard Of Oz (Adaptations)}}\n[[Category:Works based on The Wizard of Oz]]\n[[Category:Works based on novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Adaptations of ''The Wizard of Oz''}}\n[[File:Tin-Man-poster-Hamlin.jpeg|thumb|Poster for Fred R. Hamlin's 1902 musical extravaganza, the first major theatrical adaptation of ''The Wizard of Oz'']]\n\n''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1900 [[children's literature|children's novel]] written by American author [[L. Frank Baum]]. Since its first publication in 1900, it has been adapted many times: for film, television, theatre, books, comics, games, and other media.\n\n==Film==\n'''Live-Action'''\n* ''[[The Fairylogue and Radio-Plays]]'' is a 1908 multimedia presentation made by [[L. Frank Baum]] which featured the young silent film actress [[Romola Remus]].\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1910 film)|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 15-minute 1910 film, based on the [[The Wizard of Oz (1902 stage play)|1902 stage musical]], directed by [[Otis Turner]], and may have featured [[Bebe Daniels]] as Dorothy.\n* ''[[The Patchwork Girl of Oz (1914 film)|The Patchwork Girl of Oz]]'' is a 1914 adaptation produced by Baum's live-action motion picture company, [[The Oz Film Manufacturing Company]]. It follows the adventures of Ojo, Unc Nunkle, and Patchwork Girl in their quest for the ingredients needed for a magic potion.\n* ''[[His Majesty, the Scarecrow of Oz]]'' is a loose 1914 adaptation by Baum that became the basis for the book ''[[The Scarecrow of Oz]]''.\n* ''[[The Magic Cloak of Oz]]'' (1914) is another in the series produced by Baum himself via The Oz Film Manufacturing Company. It follows the story of Fluff, the unhappiest person in Oz, and a magic cloak fairies devised for him to grant her one wish.\n* ''[[Wizard of Oz (1925 film)|Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1925 film, directed by [[Larry Semon]] in collaboration with [[Frank Joslyn Baum]] and featuring a young [[Oliver Hardy]].\n\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is the 1939 musical film by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], directed by [[Victor Fleming]] and starring [[Judy Garland]], [[Ray Bolger]], [[Jack Haley]], [[Bert Lahr]], [[Margaret Hamilton (actress)|Margaret Hamilton]], and [[Frank Morgan]]. It is the story's best-known adaptation.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Land of Oz]]'' is a 1969 low-budget children's film adaptation of ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz]]'', directed by [[Barry Mahon]].\n* ''[[Ay\u015fecik ve Sihirli C\u00fcceler R\u00fcyalar \u00dclkesinde]]'' is a 1971 Turkish film, directed by [[Tun\u00e7 Ba\u015faran]] known to bootleggers as \"The Turkish Wizard of Oz\".\n* ''[[Oz (1976 film)|Oz]]'' is a 1976 Australian rock musical film, also known as ''Oz \u2013 A Rock 'n' Roll Road Movie'' or ''20th Century Oz''.\n* ''[[The Wiz (film)|The Wiz]]'' is a 1978 film directed by [[Sidney Lumet]] starring [[Diana Ross]] as Dorothy and [[Michael Jackson]] as the Scarecrow, based on the [[The Wiz|Broadway musical of the same name]].\n* ''[[Return to Oz]]'' is a 1985 film by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], directed by [[Walter Murch]] and starring [[Fairuza Balk]] as Dorothy.\n* ''[[The Wizard of the City of Emeralds]]'' is a 1994 Russian film version of [[Alexander Melentyevich Volkov]]'s \"adaptation\" of Baum's original book.\n* ''[[The Muppets' Wizard of Oz]]'' (2005) Starring [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Queen Latifah]] and [[The Muppets]]. [[Miss Piggy]] plays all of the witches, [[Pepe the Prawn|Pepe]] plays Toto, [[Kermit the Frog|Kermit]] plays the Scarecrow, [[Gonzo the Great|Gonzo]] plays the Tin Man, and [[Fozzie the Bear|Fozzie]] plays the Lion.\n* ''[[Apocalypse Oz]]'' (2006) is a [[short film]] parody of ''The Wizard of Oz'' and ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''.\n* ''[[After the Wizard]]'' is a 2012 independent film as a modern-day semi-sequel to the story.\n* ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]'' is a 2013 film by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], directed by [[Sam Raimi]] and starring [[James Franco]] and [[Mila Kunis]].\n* ''[[OzLand]]'' (2014) is an independent fantasy/sci-fi drama film inspired by characters and events from the book, which plays a crucial role.\n\n'''Animation'''\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1933 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1933 animated short directed by Ted Eshbaugh.\n* ''[[Journey Back to Oz]]'' is a 1971 animated film, begun in 1962, finished in 1971 and eventually released between 1972\u201374.\n* ''[[Once Upon a Time (1976 film)|Once Upon a Time]]'' is a 1976 film in which Maria and Mary-Lou get sucked down a well into Holleland. It is loosely based upon, and also pays homage to, ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* ''[[Legends of Oz: Dorothy's Return]]'' (2014) is an American-Indian 3D animated musical adaptation of ''[[Dorothy of Oz (book)|Dorothy of Oz]]'' by [[Roger S. Baum]] and stars [[Lea Michele]].\n* ''[[Guardians of Oz]]'' is a 2015 [[Mexico|Mexican]]-[[India]]n 3D computer animated adventure film directed by Alberto Mar. It features an original story and new characters.\n* ''[[The Steam Engines of Oz]]'' is a 2018 [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Animated film]] directed by [[Sean O'Reilly]] which is produced by [[Arcana Studio]]. It tells the story of Oz a hundred years later and features new characters as well as old ones.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://collider.com/william-shatner-on-the-steam-engines-of-oz-and-his-life-long-love-of-animation/|title=William Shatner on 'The Steam Engines of Oz' and His Life-Long Love of Animation|date=2018-06-05|work=Collider|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nMany of the television programs cited in this list are not strict adaptions of ''The Wizard of Oz''; rather, they have reinterpreted aspects of the book, such as characters and plot, to create sequels, prequels or side-plots, which are inspired by Baum's original text.\n* ''[[The Suite Life on Deck]]'' episode \"Twister\"\n* ''[[Back at the Barnyard]]'' the last part of the episode \"Lights! Camera! Moo!\"\n* ''[[Kappa Mikey]]'' \"The Wizard of Ozu\"\n* ''[[Rainbow Road to Oz]]'' was a proposed [[Walt Disney]] live-action production. A preview segment aired in 1957 on the ''[[Disneyland (TV series)|Disneyland]]'' TV show, featuring [[Darlene Gillespie]] as Dorothy, [[Annette Funicello]] as Ozma, [[Bobby Burgess]] as the Scarecrow, [[Doreen Tracey]] as Scraps, the Patchwork Girl, and [[Jimmie Dodd]] as the Cowardly Lion.\n* ''The Land of Oz'' is the 1960 premiere episode of ''The Shirley Temple Show'', known in previous seasons as ''[[Shirley Temple's Storybook]]'', and no relation to the ''Shirley Temple Theatre'' which showcased old Temple films. This adaptation of ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz]]'' was written by [[Frank Gabrielson]] and directed by William Corrigan. [[William Asher]] produced. The cast included [[Shirley Temple]] (Ozma/Tip), [[Ben Blue]] (The Scarecrow), [[Agnes Moorehead]] (Mombi), [[Sterling Holloway]] (Jack Pumpkinhead), [[Gil Lamb]] (The Tin Woodman), [[Jonathan Winters]] (Lord Nikidik), [[Arthur Treacher]] (Graves the Butler), and [[Mel Blanc]] (Voice of the sawhorse).\n* ''[[Tales of the Wizard of Oz]]'' is a [[1961 in television|1961]] animated series of short episodes based on the Oz characters from the book.\n* ''[[Off to See the Wizard]]'' is a 1967 television anthology series which showcased then-recent MGM family films. The Oz characters appeared in animated segments.\n* ''[[Return to Oz (TV program)|Return to Oz]]'' is a [[1964 in television|1964]] animated television special sequel-cum-remake of the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]], based on the artistic renderings of the characters in the [[Tales of the Wizard of Oz|1961 animated series]].\n* ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', on February 16, 1980, had a sketch called ''The Incredible Man'', a parody of both ''The Wizard of Oz'' and the annual TV broadcast of the film that was standard at the time.   \n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1982 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a feature-length anime adaptation of the story produced by [[Toho]] in 1982 and directed by Fumihiko Takayama, with music by [[Joe Hisaishi]]. The English version of the movie stars [[Aileen Quinn]] as the voice of Dorothy and [[Lorne Greene]] as the Wizard. Original songs are sung by Aileen Quinn in the English version, with lyrics by [[Sammy Cahn]] and Allen Byrnes. It was released in the United States before it premiered in Japan. In the U.S., it was released on video and syndicated to local television stations.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1986 TV series)|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', an episodic anime adaptation of four of Baum's Oz books, was created in 1986. It consists of 52 episodes and follows the story of Dorothy and her adventures in Oz with the Tin Woodman, Cowardly Lion, and Scarecrow. It continues on to the story of [[Princess Ozma|Ozma]] and [[Mombi]], and follows the events in other Oz books. In 1987, HBO purchased the rights to the series and edited together key episodes of the series into a series of movies, which aired as a television mini-series. [[Margot Kidder]] was the narrator. Production for the English version was done by the Canadian studio [[Cinar]].\n* In the 1987 series ''[[Hello Kitty's Furry Tale Theater]]'', ''The Wizard of Paws'' is the first part of first episode. The story begins when after a huge tornado, Hello Dorothy (Hello Kitty) gets whisked away from her home of Catfish to The Land of Paws. Upon arrival, she is welcomed by the Tin Penguin (Tuxedo J Orville Sam), The Scarecrow (Chip), the Cowardly Rabbit (My Melody) and the Munchkits. They thank Hello Dorothy, as the Wicked Witch (Catnip) was about to turn them into cat litter. Just as that is said, the Wicked Witch arises from the house as hello kitty picks up the ruby collar. After crushing the Wicked Witch and taking her collar, the witch plans revenge on Hello Dorothy to take back her precious collar. Dorothy then begins her journey back to the land of Catfish with the penguin, scarecrow and rabbit in order to return home along the yellow block road.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (TV series)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', an animated series based on the 1939 film, was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] during the [[1990 in television|1990\u20131991 TV season]]. The cartoon featured Dorothy returning to Oz, reuniting with her four friends, and journeying through the magical realm in an attempt to rescue the Wizard from a resurrected Witch of the West.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Galaxy of Oz]]'' (''Space Oz no B\u00f4ken'') is a [[1990 in television|1990]] Japanese anime series involving Dorothy and her friends in a futuristic setting, traveling the \"Galaxy of Oz\". It was truncated to 76 minutes and dubbed for the American release.\n* ''[[The Oz Kids]]'' is a [[1996 in television|1996]] animated series by [[Hyperion Pictures]] and [[Nelvana]] featuring the children of the original characters.\n* ''[[Tim Burton's unrealized projects#2000s|Tim Burton's Lost In Oz]]'' is a [[2000 in television|2000]] unrealized television pilot script written by [[Trey Callaway]] with [[Tim Burton]] as executive producer. Key scenes were filmed by [[Michael Katleman]].\n* ''Lost in Oz'' is a [[2002 in television|2002]] television pilot, never broadcast. It is a sequel to the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]].\n* The ''[[Futurama]]'' episode \"[[Anthology of Interest II]]\" is a retelling of the Oz story, shown as a dream of one of the show's characters.\n* The 100th episode of the television comedy-drama show ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', titled \"[[My Way Home (Scrubs)|My Way Home]]\" is a homage to the ''Wizard of Oz''.\n* ''[[Tin Man (TV miniseries)|Tin Man]]'' is a three-part miniseries released in December 2007 on the [[Syfy|Sci-fi Channel]] by [[RHI Entertainment]] and Syfy. The miniseries, directed by [[Nick Willing]] and starring [[Zooey Deschanel]], [[Richard Dreyfuss]], [[Alan Cumming]], [[Raoul Trujillo]], [[Neal McDonough]], and [[Kathleen Robertson]], is a re-imagined version of ''The Wizard of Oz'' with a heavy science fantasy emphasis. The heroine, D.G., is a descendant of Dorothy Gale. Other humans, called \"Slippers\" by the people of Oz, have visited Oz since Gale's fateful adventure. The series portrays a future version of Oz, thereby making the mini-series both a sequel and a re-imagining.\n* ''OzEnders'', a 2003 charity special of ''[[EastEnders]]'', saw the characters in a spoof remake of ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''. [[June Brown]] starred as [[Dot Cotton|Dorothy Cotton]], [[Jon Culshaw]] as [[Ozzy Osbourne]], and [[Adam Woodyatt]] as [[Ian Beale]].\n* ''[[The Witches of Oz]]'' is a 2011 television mini-series directed by Leigh Scott, based on the novels ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'', ''Ozma of Oz'', ''The Road to Oz'', and ''The Magic of Oz'' by Baum.\n* An episode of ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'' shows SpongeBob and Patrick going to see Mr. Magic. As in ''The Wizard of Oz'', Mr. Magic, who was thought to be a giant, magical head, is revealed to be a powerless, little man.\n* In 2012 the [[Nickelodeon]] show ''[[The Fresh Beat Band]]'' did a remake in a one hour episode called \u201cThe Wizard of Song\u201d with Mariana as Dorothy, Kiki as Tin-women, Twist as Scarecrow, and Shout as the Lion.\n* ''[[Tom and Jerry and the Wizard of Oz]]'' is a ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' direct-to-video film, the first to be made for [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]]. It first appeared on [[Cartoon Network]] on August 13, 2011. It was followed by a sequel, ''[[Tom and Jerry: Back to Oz]]'', released February 3, 2016.\n* In an episode of ''[[Rugrats]]'', ''[[No Place Like Home (Rugrats episode)|No Place Like Home]]'', Susie dreams of a land like Oz after having her tonsils removed.\n* In an episode of ''[[The Wonder Pets]]'' ''In the Land of Oz'', The Wonder Pets get caught in a tornado and blown to the magical Land of Oz, and they need help getting home by The Scarecrow, The Tin Man and The Cowardly Lion by going to the Emerald City.\n* An episode of ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' is titled ''[[Wizard of Odd]]''. In order to wash their house quickly, Phineas and Ferb build a contraption that spins it around, causing Candace to become so dizzy, she collapses. She soon finds herself in the magical land of Odd where Isabella, Dr. Doofenshmirtz, Jeremy, Buford, and Baljeet are remarkably like the characters from ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* An episode of ''[[Mickey Mouse Clubhouse]]'', \"Minnie's The Wizard of Dizz\", places Minnie and Pluto in the roles of Dorothy and Toto. Goofy, Mickey, and Donald appear as the Scarecrow, Tin Mouse, and Lion. Clarabelle Cow appears as the good witch, Pete as the bad witch, and Ludwig von Drake as the wizard.\n* The characters Dorothy Gale and The Wicked Witch of the West make appearances in the 2014 episode \"Slumber Party\" from the ninth season of the television series ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''. Dorothy is revealed to be a hunter of evil and the daughter of [[L. Frank Baum]]. The Tin Man, Cowardly Lion, and Scarecrow all make appearances. The [[Supernatural (season 10)|season 10]] episode \"There's No Place Like Home\" tells of a war for the Emerald City in which the Wizard has been split into good and dark sides.\n* The Wicked Witch of the West is the main antagonist in the second half of the third season of the ABC/Disney television series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''. In this version, the wicked witch was abandoned by her mother in the woods where a tornado took her to Oz.\n* ''[[Emerald City (TV series)|Emerald City]]'' is a television series in development by [[Universal Television]] that drew inspiration from L. Frank Baum's original 14 books. Created by [[Matthew Arnold (director)|Matthew Arnold]], in January 2014 it had been officially picked up by [[NBC]] for 10 episodes.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/23/nbc-wizard-of-oz-emerald-city_n_3805939.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Leigh | last=Weingus | title='The Wizard Of Oz' Just Keeps Getting Hotter | date=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/20/nbc-picks-up-emerald-city_n_4630556.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Jason | last=Hughes | title=Welcome To 'Emerald City'}}</ref> In August 2014, it was reported that NBC would not be proceeding with the series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=NBC Drops Limited Series ''Emerald City''|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nbc-drops-limited-series-emerald-727155|website=The Live Feed: [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=23 August 2014|date=22 August 2014}}</ref> In April 2015, NBC reversed course and announced that the series would move forward under the leadership of executive producer and writer [[David Schulner]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/emerald-city-resurrected-nbc-series-1201410547 | work=Deadline.com | first=Nellie | last=Andreeva | title=\u2018Emerald City\u2019 Resurrected By NBC With Straight-To-Series Order, New Writer | date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n* On December 3, 2015, [[NBC]] aired the live television production ''[[The Wiz Live!]]'' Produced by Craig Zadan and Neil Meron, it is a performance of a new adaptation of the 1975 Broadway musical ''[[The Wiz]]'', a soul/R&B reinterpretation of L. Frank Baum's ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz''. The performance aired live from [[Grumman Studios]] in Bethpage, New York.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web |title=The Wiz Live! Defied The Skeptics, Returns For A Second Round |url=https://www.npr.org/2015/12/19/460313984/the-wiz-live-defied-the-skeptics-returns-for-a-second-round |date=December 20, 2015 |publisher=NPR |accessdate=January 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=NBC>{{cite web |title=The Wiz Live! |url=http://www.nbc.com/the-wiz-live |publisher=NBC |accessdate=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n* On June 26, 2015, [[Amazon Video]] released an original 24-minute pilot for an animated series, ''[[Lost In Oz (TV series)|Lost in Oz]]''.  On November 2, 2016, it was re-released with additional content under the title ''[[Lost in Oz: Extended Adventure]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lost in Oz (TV Series 2015\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4677846|accessdate=2017-06-27}}</ref> The series aired on August 4, 2017.\n* ''[[Dorothy and the Wizard of Oz]]'' (originally ''Dorothy: Princess of Oz'' and ''Dorothy of Oz'') is an animated series produced by [[Warner Bros. Animation]]. It was released in June 2017 for [[Boomerang (TV network)|Boomerang]]'s SVOD service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/boomerang-cartoon-streaming-subscription-time-warner-turner-wb-1202003660/|title=Turner, Warner Bros. to Launch Boomerang Cartoon Streaming-Subscription Service for $5 Monthly|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2017-03-07|work=Variety|access-date=2017-06-27|language=en-US}}</ref> Clips of the series were revealed in the Boomerang upfront for 2017.<ref>https://vimeo.com/200963930</ref>\n* In the ''[[Victorious]]'' episode \"April Fools' Blank\", the main characters retell the story in the girls' toilet of the Hollywood Arts.\n* In the rebooted TV series [[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|Dynasty]] episode \"That Witch\", one of the main characters [[Fallon Carrington Colby|Fallon]], gets knocked by an ornament and sees visions of herself as Dorothy in the Wizard of Oz.\n\n==Theatre==\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1902 stage play)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', the first [[musical theater|musical]] version of ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'', was produced by L. Frank Baum and W. W. Denslow (with music by composer [[Paul Tietjens]]) in [[Chicago]] in 1902 and moved to New York in 1903. It used many of the same characters, and was aimed more at adult audiences. It had a long, successful run on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. Baum added numerous political references to the script, mentioning President [[Theodore Roosevelt]], Senator [[Mark Hanna]], and [[John D. Rockefeller]] by name.<ref>Swartz, ''Before the Rainbow'', pp 34, 47, 56</ref> Many existing songs that had nothing to do with the story were interpolated. Baum followed with two additional Oz musicals, ''[[The Woggle-Bug]]'' (1905) and ''[[The Tik-Tok Man of Oz]]'' (1913). Both were panned as rehashes rather than sequels; ''Tik-Tok'' did better than ''The Woggle-Bug'' but neither made it to Broadway.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1942 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1942 musical using songs from the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]]. It was adapted by [[Frank Gabrielson]] for the [[St. Louis Municipal Opera]]. The piece continues to receive frequent revivals.<ref name=\"stage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beyondtherainbow2oz.com/stagethewizard.html|title=We're Off To Stage The Wizard of Oz|accessdate=2007-07-15|last=Raymond|first=Kurt|work=Beyond the Rainbow to Oz website| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714185622/http://www.beyondtherainbow2oz.com/stagethewizard.html| archivedate= 14 July 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tams-witmark.com/musicals/wizardrsc.html |title=Wizard of Oz (R.S.C. 1988) |accessdate=2007-07-15 |year=2005 |publisher=Tams\u2013Witmark Music Library |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701001053/http://www.tams-witmark.com/musicals/wizardrsc.html |archivedate=1 July 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 1959, the popular ice skating show ''[[Holiday on Ice]]'' included a condensed version of ''The Wizard of Oz''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vintage Holiday On Ice Show Programs|url=http://www.icesk8.com/collect/progrm01.htm|work=Ice Skating Accessories Galore Collectible Skating Programs|publisher=Lisa Ilona Hlavacek|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wiz]]'' is a 1975 musical with music and lyrics by [[Charlie Smalls]], exclusively featuring [[African American]] actors. [[Stephanie Mills]] starred as Dorothy in the original Broadway cast. The production won the 1975 [[Tony Award]] for [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]]. [[Geoffrey Holder]] directed a 1984 Broadway revival, which also featured Mills as Dorothy.\n* ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz (musical)|The Marvelous Land of Oz]]'' is a 1981 musical by Thomas W. Olson, Gary Briggle and [[Richard Dworsky]]. The original production, which included Briggle as the Scarecrow, was taped and shown on television.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 1987 adaptation by [[John Kane (writer)|John Kane]] for the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] based on the novel and 1939 film, which hews more closely to the film's screenplay than the 1942 version. This show ran through 1989 and continues to be frequently revived and toured.<ref>[http://www.columbiaartiststheatricals.com/Shows/wizard_oz.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612104931/http://www.columbiaartiststheatricals.com/Shows/wizard_oz.html|date=June 12, 2008}}</ref><ref>[http://www.timescolonist.com/entertainment/Follow+yellow+brick+road/3862399/story.html]{{dead link|date=November 2015}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wizard of A.I.D.S.]]'' is a 1987 adaptation of the Oz story which serves as an [[AIDS]] education tool.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz Live]]'' (1989\u20131990) is an arena touring production in celebration of the film's 50th anniversary. The production featured a pre-recorded soundtrack.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz in Concert: Dreams Come True]]'' was a 1995 concert performance of the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]'s adaptation at [[Lincoln Center]], featuring celebrity actors such as [[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]] as Dorothy, [[Jackson Browne]] as the Scarecrow, [[Roger Daltrey]] as the Tin Man, [[Nathan Lane]] as the Lion, and [[Joel Grey]] as the Wizard (a role he later reprised in [[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]). The production also featured [[Debra Winger]], [[Natalie Cole]], and [[Lucie Arnaz]].\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz on Tour]]'' was a 1998 touring production of the 1987 RSC version that originally played in the [[Madison Square Garden]] theatre in May 1997. [[Roseanne Barr]] was the Wicked Witch, replaced by [[Eartha Kitt]] in 1998 and [[JoAnne Worley]] and [[Liliane Montevecchi]] in 1999. [[Mickey Rooney]] was the Wizard. The production played at Madison Square Garden from May 1997 to May 1999. The touring production ran from May 1998 to late 1999.\n* ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]'' (2003\u2013Present) is a 2003 Broadway and West End musical based on the book ''[[Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West]]'' by [[Gregory Maguire]]. [[Universal Pictures]] had bought [[film rights]] to the 1995 novel when composer and lyricist [[Stephen Schwartz (composer)|Stephen Schwartz]] convinced the company to adapt the novel into a musical instead. Schwartz wrote ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''{{'}}s music and lyrics and it premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in October 2003.<ref name=\"Christie\"/>\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (musical)]]'' is a 2000 musical that premiered in Toronto. The show was revived in 2002, 2010 and again in 2017.\n* In 2005 there was a children musical in [[Balver H\u00f6hle]]\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (2011 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' is a 2011 West End musical, building on the 1939 film songs and script with new material by Tim Rice and Andrew Lloyd Webber. It began previews on February 7, 2011 and officially opened on March 1. [[Danielle Hope]], of the [[BBC]] television Series ''[[Over the Rainbow (2010 TV series)|Over the Rainbow]]'', appeared as Dorothy. [[Michael Crawford]] plays the role of the Wizard.\n* ''The [[Royal New Zealand Ballet]] premiered a ''Wizard of Oz'' ballet in May 2016 at the [[St. James Theatre, Wellington]] using a score created by composer [[Francis Poulenc]]. The ballet then toured New Zealand throughout May and June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=RNZB website|url=http://rnzb.org.nz/shows/the-wizard-of-oz/|work=RNZB show page|publisher=Royal New Zealand Ballet|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n* In 2015, a [[Costa Rica]]n adaptation of both the novel and the [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|1939 film]] titled ''El OH!8'' was premiered. The stage play is an open criticism of the country's laws against [[LGBT marriage]], using the original plot and similar musical numbers.\n* In 2018, musical \"\u010carobnjak iz Oza\" premieref in Children's Theatre in [[Osijek]], Croatia.<ref name=\"\u010carobnjak iz Oza\">{{cite web | title=Premijera mjuzikla \u010carobnjak iz Oza | trans-title=The Musical Premiere of the Wizard of Oz | website=Osnovna \u0161kola August \u0160enoa Osijek | url=http://os-asenoa-os.skole.hr/?news_hk=1&news_id=1962&mshow=1534#mod_news | language=hr | access-date=2018-05-16 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517005934/http://os-asenoa-os.skole.hr/?news_hk=1&news_id=1962&mshow=1534#mod_news | archive-date=2018-05-17 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nThere are over [[List of Oz books|40 canonical Oz books]], including 14 by Baum, all of which are considered \"official\" sequels or prequels to ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]''. In addition, the following books use the Oz milieu as settings for their tales:\n* ''[[The Wizard of the Emerald City]]'', a 1939 children's novel by Russian writer [[Alexander Melentyevich Volkov]], is a loose translation of ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz''. It was adapted into animated series (1973)<ref>{{cite web|title=Volshebnik izumrudnogo goroda (1974)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0069653/|work=IMDb.com|publisher=IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> and a live action film (1994).<ref>{{cite web|title=Volshebnik izumrudnogo goroda (1994)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0111641/|work=IMDb.com|publisher=IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> It has five sequels by the same author.\n* ''[[The Number of the Beast (novel)|The Number of the Beast]]'' is a science fiction novel written by [[Robert A. Heinlein]] in 1980. The story uses Oz as one of many alternate universe settings in which events take place, alongside alternate versions of the setting's Earth.\n* ''[[A Barnstormer in Oz]]'' is a 1982 novel by [[Philip Jos\u00e9 Farmer]] in which a pilot named Hank Stover, who is Dorothy's son, is transported to Oz when his plane becomes lost in a green cloud over Kansas.\n* ''[[Was (novel)|Was]]'', [[Geoff Ryman]]'s 1992 [[parallel novel]], imagines three interwoven narratives: one of a real-life \"Dorothy Gael\" whose experiences are far from wonderful, the second loosely based on Judy Garland's own childhood, and the third story featuring a gay male actor who loves the 1939 film. ''Was'' was republished in 2014 by [[Small Beer Press]].\n* ''Home from Oz'' (Thomas Nelson, 1994) and ''The Oz Syndrome'' (Hillcrest Publishers, 2001) are two books penned by psychologist and professor, Dr.[[Michael A. O'Donnell]] which deal with the Oz characters and the [[MGM]] musical version from a psychological point of view.\n* ''[[Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West]]'', a revisionist look at the land and characters of Oz, was published in 1995 by [[Gregory Maguire]]. Instead of depicting Dorothy, the novel focuses on [[Elphaba]], the future Wicked Witch of the West. ''[[The Independent]]'' characterized the novel as \"an adult read reflecting on the nature of being an outcast, society's pressures to conform, and the effects of oppression and fascism\".<ref name=\"Christie\">{{cite news|title=Wicked: tales of the witches of Oz |author=Christie, Nicola |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/wicked--tales-of-the-witches-of-oz-412263.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=August 17, 2006 |accessdate=February 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705183310/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/wicked--tales-of-the-witches-of-oz-412263.html |archivedate=July 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Wicked'' has three sequels: ''[[Son of a Witch]]'' (2005), ''[[A Lion Among Men]]'' (2008) and ''[[Out of Oz]]'' (2011). ''Wicked'' was adapted into a 2003 stage musical.\n* ''[[Oz Reimagined: New Tales from the Emerald City and Beyond]]'' is a 2013 anthology edited by Douglas Cohen & [[John Joseph Adams]] published by [[Amazon Publishing]]'s 47North imprint.<ref>{{cite web|title=You\u2019ve never seen the Wizard of Oz like this before)|url=http://io9.com/5953680/youve-never-seen-the-wizard-of-oz-like-this-before|work=io9|publisher=io9|accessdate=22 October 2012|author=Jane Anders, Charlie |date=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Dorothy Must Die]]'' is a 2014 young adult book by Danielle Paige and makes up part of the ''Dorothy Must Die'' series, which also includes three prequel novellas: ''No Place Like Oz'', ''The Witch Must Burn'' and ''The Wizard Returns'', which were published together in March 2015. The next three prequel novellas, ''Heart of Tin'', ''The Straw King'' and ''Ruler of Beasts'', were released in a paperback book titled ''Dorothy Must Die Stories: Volume #2'' in June 28, 2016. Two more novellas, ''Order of the Wicked'' and ''Dark Side of the Rainbow'', have also been released. A sequel titled ''[[The Wicked Will Rise]]'' was published on March 30, 2015, following the events of ''Dorothy Must Die''. The third installment of the series titled ''Yellow Brick War'' was published on March 15, 2016. The fourth and final book, ''The End of Oz'', was published on March 14, 2017.\n\n==Comics==\n[[File:WiZardOz.jpg|thumb|260px|''The Wizard of Oz'' ([[Dell Comics]], June 1956). Cover art by Mel Crawford.]]\n* MGM's ''Marvelous Wizard of Oz'' was the first joint publishing venture between [[DC Comics]] and [[Marvel Comics]].<ref>{{cite book|last=McAvennie|first= Michael|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1970s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 165 |quote = The Yellow Brick Road from Munchkin Land to the Emerald City was also wide enough to accommodate DC and Marvel as they produced their first-ever joint publication&nbsp;... Roy Thomas scripted a faithful, seventy-two page adaptation of Dorothy Gale's adventure, while John Buscema's artwork depicted the landscape of Oz in lavish detail.}}</ref>\n* Marvel Treasury of Oz printed ''[[The Marvelous Land of Oz]]''.\n* One of the issues of ''[[Classics Illustrated Junior]]'' was a condensed version of ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* The comic book series ''[[Oz Squad]]'' features an adult Dorothy and her original companions from ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' as a [[covert operations]] group protecting Oz from threats both within its borders and from the \"real world\".\n* ''The Oz-Wonderland War'' is a comics story in which the people of Oz fight together with the characters of [[Lewis Carroll]]'s ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Through the Looking-Glass]]'' against the villainous [[Nome King]]. It also starred [[Captain Carrot]] and the [[Zoo Crew]] and was originally intended to be the comic's issues #21\u201326. The comic, however, was cancelled at #20, and the story was subsequently presented as a mini-series.\n* ''[[Dorothy of Oz (manhwa)|Dorothy of Oz]]'' (Korean:''Dorosi'') is a [[manhwa]] (Korean comic) by Son Hee-joon about an ordinary girl named Mara Shin who winds up in a science-fantasy realm called \"Oz\". She meets up with this realm's version of the Scarecrow, the Tin Woodsman and the Cowardly Lion, and follows the Yellow Brick Road to find her way home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animeondvd.com/reviews2/manga/manga.php?manga_view=4079 |title=AnimeOnDVD.com review of Dorothy of Oz |accessdate=6 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506094208/http://www.animeondvd.com/reviews2/manga/manga.php?manga_view=4079 |archivedate=6 May 2008 }}</ref>\n* The comic book ''[[Dorothy (comic book)|Dorothy]]'' was launched by Illusive Arts Entertainment in November 2005. Presented in semi-[[Photo strip|fumetti]] style using digitally altered photographs, this retelling of Baum's story has been updated to 2005 and features model Catie Fisher as 16-year-old Dorothy Gale, a disaffected youth with dyed hair and piercings who steals her uncle's car and runs away from home; until she encounters a tornado and is knocked unconscious.\n* An erotic re-telling of the story is featured in ''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]'', a graphic novel by [[Alan Moore]] and [[Melinda Gebbie]] first published in its entirety in 2006. In this book, an adult Dorothy meets [[Alice (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Alice]] from ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' and [[Wendy Darling]] from ''[[Peter Pan]]'' and the trio recount the stories of their respective works as allegories for their sexual awakenings.\n* ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (comics)|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', published by [[Marvel Comics]].\n* ''[[Marvel Fairy Tales]]'' features a retelling of ''The Wizard of Oz'' starring Marvel characters, such as the [[She-Hulk]] as Dorothy and the [[Scarlet Witch]] as the Wicked Witch of the West.   \n* The Steam Engines of Oz is a graphic novel series published by [[Arcana Studio]]. It is a \"steampunk re-imagining\" of [[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rotoscopers.com/2017/11/04/animated-steampunk-wizard-of-oz-set-for-2018/|title=Animated Steampunk 'Wizard of Oz' Set for 2018 {{!}} Rotoscopers|date=2017-11-04|work=Rotoscopers|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Games==\n* ''The Wonderful Game of Oz'', a board game published in 1921 by [[Parker Brothers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/14261/wonderful-game-of-oz |title=Wonderful Game of OZ |publisher=BoardGameGeek |date=May 4, 2005 |accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1985 video game)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', a 1985 illustrated [[text adventure]] game for [[Apple II]], [[Commodore 64]] and [[DOS]] systems,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mocagh.org/loadpage.php?getgame=wizardoz |title=Computer Game Museum Display Case \u2013 Wizard of Oz |publisher=Mocagh.org |date=2001-07-07 |accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lysator.liu.se/adventure/Telarium_Corporation.html |title=Telarium Corporation |publisher=Lysator.liu.se |date=1930-11-09 |accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref> which combined elements of ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' and ''The Marvelous Land of Oz''. It was published by [[Windham Classics]], a subsidiary of [[Spinnaker Software]].\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (video game)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', a 1993 video game for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]], based on the 1939 film.\n* ''[[The Wizard of Oz (arcade game)|The Wizard of Oz]]'', a coin pusher game found in video arcades.\n* ''Wizard of Land Oz'' (''\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0448\u0435\u0431\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044b \u041e\u0437''), a 1997 [[ZX Spectrum]] adventure game by Famous Faces Factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/infoseekid.cgi?id=0013128 |title=Wizard of Land Oz |publisher=World of Spectrum |date= |accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref>\n* ''[[Irozuki Tincle no Koi no Balloon Trip]]'', a Japanese game which is a spin-off of ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series. It features [[Tingle (character)|Tingle]] teaming up with a tin woman, a scarecrow and a cowardly lion to cross the land. Released in 2009.\n* ''[[Emerald City Confidential]]'', a point-and-click adventure game developed by [[Dave Gilbert (game designer)|Wadjet Eye Games]] and published by casual game portal [[PlayFirst]]. Released in 2009.\n* ''RIZ-ZOAWD'', a Japanese [[role-playing video game]] for the [[Nintendo DS]], released in the US as ''[[The Wizard of Oz: Beyond the Yellow Brick Road]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Riz-Zoawd Hands-On Preview|url=http://www.1up.com/previews/riz-zoawd|work=1UP Games.com|publisher=1UP Games|accessdate=23 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104102742/http://www.1up.com/previews/riz-zoawd|archivedate=4 November 2012}}</ref> Released in 2008.\n* ''Wizard of Oz Slots game'' found in Casinos. The game is a five-reel video slot machine with bonus feature rounds, produced by [[Williams Electronics|WMS]] (WIlliams Gaming). Released in 2013.\n* ''The Card Game of Oz'', a 2014 game created by James C. O'Connor under his Orion's Bell label.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orion's Bell|url=http://www.orionsbell.com|publisher=Orion's Bell|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> The game is based on the original books. Series 1, ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'', was released in May 2014. Series 2, ''The Marvelous Land of Oz'', was released in August 2014 as an expansion.\n* The crossover-genre video game ''[[Lego Dimensions]]'' features a world based on the 1939 film.\n* The mobile game ''Oz: Broken Kingdom'' Is based on the world of Oz and takes place after the original story.\n\n== Music videos with Wizard of Oz themed imagery ==\n* The band [[Blues Traveler]]'s video of the song \"[[Run-Around (song)|Run-Around]]\" has a ''Wizard of Oz'' motif, with Blues Traveler playing behind a curtain in a nightclub while a young, \"hip\" and more \"photogenic\" group appears to be playing the song.\n* The band [[The Good Life (band)|The Good Life]]'s video for the song \"Heartbroke\" has characters from ''The Wizard of Oz'' going to a pastry/ice cream shop. There are two versions to this video; a \"nice\" version and a \"mean\" version. In the \"nice\" version the characters pretend to rob the shop but then purchase treats. In the \"mean\" version they violently rob the store, but the Scarecrow (who was supposed to be the getaway car) does not make it on time due to a flat tire and the would-be robbers get arrested.\n* The Black Eyed Peas music video \"Imma Be Rocking That Body\" has claimed to be the futuristic version of ''The Wizard of Oz''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kh1WyfCrnKM&list=UUrwmu-gceGOmtZeuTsn7DlQ|title=Black Eyed Peas \u2013 Imma Be (Making Of)|author=van BlackEyedPeasVEVO|date=|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref>\n* Tech N9ne's \"He's A Mental Giant\" follows the plot to the Wizard of Oz with darker imagery.<ref>{{Citation|last=TechN9neVEVO|title=Tech N9ne - He's A Mental Giant|date=2011-08-09|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7rhxEwJXzKo|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* \"Oooh\" by De La Soul is a music video that shows the Land of Oooh which is heavily based on the Land of Oz.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tommy Boy|title=De La Soul - Oooh (feat. Redman) [Music Video] {Clean}|date=2017-08-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uqp33KRndl8|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* Sara Evans stars as Dorothy in her music video \"Born to Fly\".<ref>{{Citation|last=saraevansVEVO|title=Sara Evans - Born To Fly|date=2009-10-02|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8xvhutWc67k|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* The music video for \"La la la\" by Naughty Boy featuring Sam Smith shows a young boy traveling around a city meeting characters resembling the Lion, the Tin Man, and the Scarecrow.<ref>{{Citation|last=NaughtyBoyVEVO|title=Naughty Boy - La la la ft. Sam Smith (Official Video)|date=2013-04-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3O1_3zBUKM8|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n* The music video for \"Heretics and Killers\" by Protest The Hero shows the flying monkeys featured in the Wizard of Oz.<ref>{{Citation|last=Vagrant Records|title=Protest The Hero - \"Heretics and Killers\" [Official Video]|date=2006-06-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEn8HmgJxd4|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n* In 1967, [[The Seekers]] recorded \"[[Emerald City (song)|Emerald City]]\", with lyrics about a visit there, set to the melody of [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s \"[[Ode to Joy]]\".\n* [[Todd McFarlane]] created a sinister toy series called ''Twisted Land of Oz'' that portrays all of the characters as more sinister (such as the monster Toto) and adult oriented (BDSM Dorothy).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Twisted Land of OZ |url=http://www.spawn.com/features/monsters2/ |work=Spawn |publisher=Spawn.com |accessdate=23 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313070532/http://www.spawn.com/features/monsters2/ |archivedate=13 March 2012 }}</ref>\n* The rock band [[Aerosmith]] put some original audios from the 1939 movie and Steven Tyler's voice repeating some quotes of the characters in the song ''The Farm'' in the album 'Nine Lives' from 1997.\n* [[Walt Disney]] originally wanted to make an animated version of ''The Wizard Of Oz'' to serve as the follow-up to ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney's long, long journey to Oz|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2006/11/03/6565.aspx#.T-WAIFIl3IU|work=Jim Hill Media|publisher=Jim Hill Media|accessdate=23 June 2012|author=Jim Hill|date=3 November 2006}}</ref> but the film rights were bought by [[Samuel Goldwyn]], who originally intended to make it as a standard musical comedy, with [[Eddie Cantor]] as his star. However, Goldwyn ended up selling the rights to MGM.\n* [[The Felice Brothers]] wrote a song called \"Don't Wake the Scarecrow\" which features several references to ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* American McGee's ''Oz'' was a darkly, twisted series of figurines based on Baum's original ''Wizard of Oz'' characters. This series was released before McFarlane's, and was supposed to help McGee launch a franchise around this interpretation.\n* ''[[Stargate SG-1]]'' has several verbal references to ''The Wizard of Oz'', including [[Colonel Jack O'Neill]] calling [[Samantha Carter]] \"Dorothy\" when she defeated one of the show's villains.\n* The band [[Scissor Sisters]] released a song on their self-titled album called \"Return to Oz\", referencing the sequel.\n* The [[John Boorman]] film ''[[Zardoz]]'' derives its title from the ''Wizard of Oz'' (The Wi'''ZARD''' of '''OZ''').<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,942780,00.html | work=Time | title=Cinema: Celtic Twilight | date=1974-02-18 | accessdate=2010-04-23}}</ref>\n* [[Elton John]]'s album ''[[Goodbye Yellow Brick Road]]'' is a clear reference to ''The Wizard of Oz''.\n* The Wiyos's album ''Twist'' is an original song cycle loosely based on ''The Wizard of Oz''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Outsight Radio Hours interviews Michael Farkas of The Wiyos on the group's Oz-inspired album Twist|url=https://archive.org/details/MichaelFarkasOnOutsightRadioHours|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Ray Bradbury]]'s short story \"[[The Exiles (Bradbury story)|The Exiles]]\" mentions the Emerald City and its inhabitants existing alongside other famous literary characters and locales on a Martian colony.\n* ''[[Big Finish Productions]]'' made a full-cast audio drama adaptation of the novel, adapted by [[Marc Platt (writer)|Marc Platt]].\n* ''[[Tom and Jerry: Back to Oz]]'' is the sequel to ''[[Tom and Jerry and the Wizard of Oz]]'' and is a ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' direct-to-video film.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\nKevin Scott Collier. ''The Wonderful Animated World of the Wizard of Oz: The Good, The Bad and The Ugly!'' CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2018. {{ISBN|172632558X}}\n\n{{Oz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wizard Of Oz (Adaptations)}}\n[[Category:Works based on The Wizard of Oz]]\n[[Category:Works based on novels]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adaptations_of_The_Wizard_of_Oz"}
